<center>
<FONT FACE="helvetica,arial" SIZE="2" color="#000000"><b>
Asynchronous Observer for a Copier Paper Path</b><br>
</b></font>
&nbsp;<br>

<FONT FACE="helvetica,arial" SIZE="2">
Martin Krucinski, Carlo Cloet, Masayoshi Tomizuka and Roberto Horowitz<br>
&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;<br>

<FONT FACE="helvetica,arial" SIZE="2" color="#000498"><b>
Abstract<br></b></font>
&nbsp;<br>
</center>

<div align=left><left>
<FONT FACE="helvetica,arial" SIZE="2">
A copier contains many sensors along its paperpath to 
detect sheet positions and velocities. Measurement information 
becomes available when a sheet crosses one 
of these sensors. The measurement time may not co
incide with the controller sample time. The longer the 
sample period, the larger the delay before the measurement 
is used. This paper presents an approach to more 
accurately process the asynchronous measurement in- 
formation without increasing the controller sampling 
frequency. An oversampled Kalman filter is used in 
between two controller sampling instants. The overall 
observer sampling rate remains equal to the controller 
sampling rate without loss in performance, since the 
Kalman filter equations can be evaluated in batch at 
the controller sampling instants. A look-up table reduces 
the computational load. <br>
&nbsp;<br>

</left></div>

&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;<br>

</td>

<td width="25"></td>
</center>
